🧠 RECORD VIEW ENGINE
Sectional Architecture for the UI / Controller System
🔷 0. PURPOSE

The Record View Engine is the governing structure for every record detail page in the system.

It defines:

✅ How a record is broken into sections
✅ How each section is governed by the engine
✅ How primary rows and child-scoped rows behave
✅ How sections are typed and configured
✅ How the engine stays shared while features stay thin

🔑 Core Definition

🔥 A record view is not a page — it is a set of section instances powered by the engine

---

🔷 1. TERMINOLOGY (AUTHORITATIVE)

These terms are fixed system-wide. Do not use deprecated terms.

✅ Current Terms

Term                   | Meaning
-----------------------|----------------------------------------------------------
PrimaryRow             | The top-level record being viewed or edited in a section
ChildScopedRow         | A child row scoped to and owned by a PrimaryRow
Section                | An isolated engine instance governing one concern of a record
FieldSection           | A section type that renders structured input fields
GridSection            | A section type that renders a row-based grid contract
RecordView             | The full page composed of one or more sections

❌ Deprecated Terms — Never Use

Deprecated Term        | Replace With
-----------------------|------------------
nested items           | ChildScopedRows
allocations (generic)  | ChildScopedRows (in engine context) — use "allocations" only for work-order inventory allocation domain logic
inline rows            | ChildScopedRows
child records          | ChildScopedRows

---

🔷 2. ENGINE POSITION

UI (render surface)
    ↓
RECORD VIEW ENGINE (section instances)
    ↓
Controller Layer (per section)
    ↓
Transport → Application → Domain → Data → Infra

Each section is a self-contained engine instance.
The engine governs — features configure.

---

🔷 3. SECTION TYPES

Every section in the system is one of these types:

🔵 1. FieldSection
Renders structured input fields for the PrimaryRow.
Governs: draft state, dirty tracking, save, discard, reconciliation.
Position: always the first section in a record view.
Example: UOM name field, Manufacturer name field, Work Order header fields.

🟢 2. GridSection
Renders a grid contract — a list of ChildScopedRows owned by the PrimaryRow.
Governs: row-level add, edit, delete, reorder, and save within the scope of the parent.
Example: Material Items under a Work Order, Template Items under a Template, Properties under a Management Company.

These are the only two section types.
Do not invent new section types without updating this engine definition.

---

🔷 4. PRIMARY ROWS

A PrimaryRow is the record that the RecordView is centered on.

Rules:
- One PrimaryRow per RecordView
- Governed by the FieldSection (first section)
- All ChildScopedRows are owned by this row
- Mutations to the PrimaryRow go through the section controller

Examples:
- Unit of Measure (UOM) record → PrimaryRow in its FieldSection
- Work Order → PrimaryRow, owns material items, service items, sales reps
- Management Company → PrimaryRow, owns properties

---

🔷 5. CHILD-SCOPED ROWS (FIRST-CLASS ENGINE ASSET)

ChildScopedRows are first-class assets of the Record View Engine.

They are NOT secondary, nested, or supplementary.
They are a governed execution unit under a parent PrimaryRow.

🔑 Definition

A ChildScopedRow is:
- Scoped to exactly one PrimaryRow
- Rendered inside a GridSection
- Created, edited, and deleted through the engine
- Subject to domain rules at the Application layer
- Reconciled back to the server snapshot after every mutation

Rules:
- ChildScopedRows are never mutated directly from the UI
- All operations flow: Controller → Transport → Application → Domain → Data
- Server snapshot replaces local state after every operation
- ChildScopedRows can have their own validation, rules, and workflows

Why ChildScopedRows Matter:
They are where the most complex execution behavior lives.
Work order material items are ChildScopedRows.
Their execution path includes inventory auto-allocation, which triggers a worker workflow.
Getting ChildScopedRow governance right means the entire system scales cleanly.

---

🔷 6. REAL EXAMPLES (SYSTEM-WIDE)

Example 1: Unit of Measures (Simple)
RecordView: UOM
  → FieldSection: General (PrimaryRow: UOM)
      Fields: name
      Save / Delete governed by section controller

Example 2: Management Company
RecordView: Management Company
  → FieldSection: General (PrimaryRow: Management Company)
      Fields: name, contact info
  → GridSection: Properties (ChildScopedRows: Properties)
      Each property is scoped to this management company
      Add / Edit / Delete governed by section controller

Example 3: Template
RecordView: Template
  → FieldSection: General (PrimaryRow: Template)
      Fields: name, warehouse, property
  → GridSection: Material Items (ChildScopedRows: Template Material Items)
  → GridSection: Service Items (ChildScopedRows: Template Service Items)
  → GridSection: Sales Reps (ChildScopedRows: Template Sales Reps)

Example 4: Work Order (Most Complex)
RecordView: Work Order
  → FieldSection: General (PrimaryRow: Work Order)
      Fields: property, status, scheduled date, warehouse
  → GridSection: Material Items (ChildScopedRows: Work Order Material Items)
      Each material item row has its own AllocationChildScopedRows
      Auto-allocation triggers a worker workflow
      This is where the execution engine is under the most load
  → GridSection: Service Items (ChildScopedRows: Work Order Service Items)
  → GridSection: Sales Reps (ChildScopedRows: Work Order Sales Reps)
  → GridSection: Calculations (read-only, derived from domain)

---

🔷 7. CHILD-SCOPED ROW DEPTH (ROWS WITHIN ROWS)

In the Work Order Material Items section, ChildScopedRows have their own sub-rows:

Work Order (PrimaryRow)
  → Material Items (ChildScopedRows, GridSection)
      → Inventory Allocations (ChildScopedRows of ChildScopedRows)

These allocation rows are domain-specific to work orders.
In the engine, both levels are ChildScopedRows.
The term "allocations" is only used in the work-order domain context — never as an engine term.

---

🔷 8. SECTION LIFECYCLE (PER SECTION INSTANCE)

Every section, regardless of type, follows this lifecycle:

mount
  ↓
load (server snapshot)
  ↓
user edits (draft state, dirty tracking)
  ↓
save triggered (controller governs)
  ↓
transport executes
  ↓
application commits
  ↓
snapshot returned
  ↓
controller reconciles (replace state)
  ↓
UI updated

This lifecycle is identical for FieldSection and GridSection.
The difference is what the section renders — not how it is governed.

---

🔷 9. ENGINE GOVERNANCE RULES (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

1. Sections are isolated
   Each section manages its own state. No section reads another's draft.

2. Controller governs all execution
   No direct API calls from UI or GridSection rows.

3. Server snapshot replaces local state
   Controller never merges. It replaces.

4. ChildScopedRows are governed like PrimaryRows
   Same execution pipeline. Same authority. No shortcuts.

5. Features provide configuration only
   The engine provides behavior. Features declare what sections exist and how they are configured.

6. Section type determines render contract — not execution contract
   Both FieldSection and GridSection use the same execution flow.

7. No business logic in the controller
   Controller orchestrates. Domain decides.

