🔷 12. WHY THIS IS GOOD FOR A SOLO DEVELOPER

Building a governed sectional engine as a solo developer is one of the highest-leverage architectural decisions you can make. Here is why:

1. You write the engine once
   Every new table, every new record view, every new section inherits your governance rules automatically. You do not rewrite state management, dirty tracking, or reconciliation for each feature. You configure.

2. Bugs fix everywhere at once
   A bug in section reconciliation logic lives in one place. Fix it once. Every record view in the system benefits. Without the engine, the same bug exists in 15 feature files and you find them one at a time.

3. You can add tables in hours, not days
   Once the engine is solid, adding a new simple record view (like a new reference table) is a configuration exercise — section type, fields, endpoint, domain rule. The lifecycle, saving, error handling, dirty tracking, and reconciliation come free.

4. Your backend execution layer scales independently
   Because the engine enforces that all mutations go through the application layer, you can harden, optimize, or reroute backend execution without touching UI or controller code. The boundary is clean.

5. Mental overhead stays low
   As a solo developer, context-switching between features is expensive. The engine creates a predictable mental model — every record view works the same way. You always know where state lives, where rules live, and where mutations happen.

6. Worker integration is safe by design
   Because ChildScopedRows already go through the full execution pipeline (Controller → Application → Domain → Data), plugging in async worker workflows (like auto-allocation) does not require architectural changes. The outbox pattern and reconciliation are already in the model.

7. The system is auditable and explainable
   When something goes wrong in production, you trace it through the same flow every time. UI → Controller → Transport → Application → Domain → Data. This is invaluable when you are the only person on call.

8. You can grow the team without chaos
   If you bring on contributors later, the engine gives them a clear contract. They configure — they do not design. The architecture does not depend on tribal knowledge.

🔥 FINAL ONE-LINER

The Record View Engine turns a complex distributed system into a repeatable configuration problem.
